The iron partition coefficient between melt and solid at the liquidus temperature (<g id="1">D</g><g id="2">Fe</g> = <g id="3">X</g><g id="4">Fe</g><g id="5">sol</g> / <g id="6">X</g><g id="7">Fe</g><g id="8">liq</g>, where <g id="9">X</g><g id="10">Fe</g><g id="11">sol</g> and <g id="12">X</g><g id="13">Fe</g><g id="14">liq</g> are the molar iron contents in the solid and liquid phases, respectively) is inferred from variations in iron content at different sample positions.
To calculate <g id="15">D</g><g id="16">Fe</g>, we combined maps of mineralogical and chemical contents, extracted from XRD and XRF respectively.
<g id="17">D</g><g id="18">Fe</g> ranges from 0.60(5) to 0.47(5) for nominal pressures of 35 GPa and 110 GPa, respectively (<g id="19">Table 1</g>, <g id="20">Fig. 4</g>).
This confirms that iron is relatively incompatible with the solid mantle.
Our <g id="21">D</g><g id="22">Fe</g> values at the lowest pressures are at the higher end of a number of experimental results obtained using multi-anvil press apparatus (see <g id="23">Supplementary Information</g>).
They are also in very good agreement with two previous studies<g id="24">19</g><g id="25">,<g id="26">20</g></g>.
